    <div class="is-prose">
      <p class="lead">In Rules to Loops, the evolution from rules to loops. In Real vs Hype, an honest look at what's real and what's hype. This part is about action: if you accept that the pattern has value — with the caveats covered in Real vs Hype — what do you actually do about it?</p>

      <p>A note on perspective: this framework is synthesised from published work by Huntley, Osmani, and Ng, practitioner accounts, and the operational realities described by supply chain professionals. Where I'm estimating rather than citing demonstrated results, I'll say so.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="is-section-rule"><hr /></div>

    <div class="is-prose">
      <h2>Before Anything: A Readiness Check</h2>
      <h4>Not every organisation should start here</h4>

      <p>Building loops on top of unreliable data or disconnected systems will amplify problems, not solve them. Before considering loops, honestly assess the foundations.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="is-readiness">
      <div class="is-readiness-col green">
        <h4>Ready to Build Loops</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Inventory data is accurate and updated in real time</li>
          <li>ERP and marketplace systems have accessible APIs</li>
          <li>Team already uses AI tools in daily work</li>
          <li>Someone understands both operations and data on the team</li>
          <li>You can define what "good" looks like for key decisions</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="is-readiness-col amber">
        <h4>Ready for Workflows, Not Yet Loops</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Data exists but is spread across spreadsheets and silos</li>
          <li>Some systems have APIs, others don't</li>
          <li>Team uses AI informally but hasn't structured it</li>
          <li>No one bridges operations and data formally</li>
          <li>Verification criteria would need to be designed from scratch</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="is-readiness-col red">
        <h4>Fix Foundations First</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Inventory accuracy below 90%</li>
          <li>Core systems lack integration capabilities</li>
          <li>No team member has used AI tools at work</li>
          <li>Processes are undocumented or inconsistent</li>
          <li>Basic supply chain firefighting is still daily reality</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="is-callout">
      <span class="is-callout-label">If you're in the red column</span>
      <p>That's not a failure — it's useful clarity. Your next investment should be data quality, system integration, and AI literacy. The loops will still be there when the foundations are ready.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="is-section-rule"><hr /></div>

    <div class="is-prose">
      <h2>Which Processes Should Get Loops?</h2>
      <h4>A four-question filter</h4>

      <p>Not every process benefits from a loop. Based on the frameworks covered in Parts 1 and 2, I'd evaluate candidates against four criteria:</p>

      <p><strong>1. Repetition frequency.</strong> How often does this decision happen? Processes that run daily or more justify loop engineering. Monthly processes probably don't.</p>

      <p><strong>2. Verification clarity.</strong> Can you objectively determine whether the output was good? If yes — stockout rate, delivery timeliness, cost variance — the loop can self-correct. If no — "was this the right strategic call?" — keep a human at that step.</p>

      <p><strong>3. Cost of a wrong decision.</strong> "$200 overpaid on one order" is acceptable risk for autonomous execution. "Lose a key supplier relationship" requires human approval.</p>

      <p><strong>4. Data accessibility.</strong> Does the loop have access to the data it needs? If the information lives in someone's head or in an email attachment, the loop can't use it.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="is-table-wrap">
